1. The debugger in CodeWarrior Java for Windows and MacOS is pretty good.
The rest of the IDE is not bad, either.

2.
&gt;How do you write tests that cause a database connection to fail after you
&gt;sent the query, but before you got the result back so that the result set
&gt;throws an exception?

In one test, use a mock object that does nothing but throws the desired
exception, instead of the real database object. In another test, use another
mock object hard-coded to return a desired result set, instead of the real
database object.

Refactoring your code to make it easy to use mock objects, also makes the
code into a better design.

3. 
&gt;This form of debugging requires visual inspection of the debug statements.
&gt;Moreover, logging debug messages at this granularity tends to reduce the
&gt;readability of the code, in my experience.

I agree. Instead of logging statements, write your own Assert class to be
used outside of JUnit, and put assertions in your code. 

Assert.assertTrue( this.ValidState() );

In the release version, write a handler for Assert exceptions that provides
a nice user-interface - at the minumum: &quot;Sorry, unexpected error&quot; +
stackcrawl.


